00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:11,440
self-directed, people choose there, if not specialties,

291
00:16:11,440 --> 00:16:15,400
and whatever draws them, the big question that draws them,

292
00:16:15,400 --> 00:16:19,360
and then explore it usually in an iterative way.

293
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:23,200
So even if an artist isn't doing the scientific method,

294
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:25,320
they're working through things over and over

295
00:16:25,320 --> 00:16:29,520
to get to something that they're trying to say,

296
00:16:29,520 --> 00:16:33,240
whether it's in or out or so.

297
00:16:33,240 --> 00:16:35,880
I think from that point of view, they're

298
00:16:35,880 --> 00:16:39,960
sort of using different tools to get to some sort of reality

299
00:16:39,960 --> 00:16:43,240
or some sort of view of the world,

300
00:16:43,240 --> 00:16:48,640
that is more in common than a lot of other things that you do.

301
00:16:48,640 --> 00:16:54,080
Yeah, I think there is basic epistemological differences.

302
00:16:54,080 --> 00:16:58,160
And certainly as far as art being a pedagogical tool

303
00:16:58,160 --> 00:17:00,240
for science, I think it's something

304
00:17:00,240 --> 00:17:01,600
that's necessary in the world.

305
00:17:01,600 --> 00:17:03,280
I think somebody brought up yesterday,

306
00:17:03,280 --> 00:17:07,960
48% of the population in the United States

307
00:17:07,960 --> 00:17:10,000
does not believe in evolution.

308
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:13,880
And there are people out there that believe the Earth is flat.

309
00:17:13,880 --> 00:17:20,400
So we need as much science and art as possible.

